Project: Investigating Human Development Index¶

Introduction¶

The information selected for the analysis is the following:

  • GDP/capita(U$, inflation adjusted): GDP per capita is gross domestic product divided by midyear population. GDP is the sum of gross value added by all resident producers in the economy plus any product taxes and minus any subsidies not included in the value of the products. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or for depletion and degradation of natural resources. Data are in constant in 2010 US Dollars. FREE DATA FROM WORLD BANK VIA GAPMINDER.ORG, CC-BY LICENSE
  • Agriculture(% of GDP): Agriculture corresponds to ISIC divisions 1-5 and includes forestry, hunting, and fishing, as well as cultivation of crops and livestock production. Value added is the net output of a sector after adding up all outputs and subtracting intermediate inputs. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or depletion and degradation of natural resources. The origin of value added is determined by the international Standard Industrial Calssification(ISIC), revision 3. Note: For for VAB countries gross value added at factor cost is ued as the denominator. FREE DATA FROM WORLD BANK VIA GAPMINDER.ORG, CC-BY LICENSE
  • Industry(% of GDP): Industry corresponds to ISIC divisions 10-45 and includes manufacturing (ISIC divisions 15-37). It comprises value added in mining, manufacturing, (also reported as a separate subgroup), construction, electricity, water, and gas. Value added is the net output of a sector after adding up all outputs and subtracting intermediate inputs. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or depletion and degradation of natural resources. The origin of value added is determined by the international Standard Industrial Calssification(ISIC), revision 3. Note: For for VAB countries gross value added at factor cost is ued as the denominator. FREE DATA FROM WORLD BANK VIA GAPMINDER.ORG, CC-BY LICENSE
  • Service (% of GDP): Services correspond to ISIC divisions 50-99 and they include value added in wholesale and retail trade(including hotels and restaurants), transport, and government, funancial, porfessional, and personal services such as education, health care, and real estate services. Also included are imputed bank service charges, import duties, and any statistical discrepancies noted by national compilers as well as discrepancies arising from rescaling. Value added is the net output of a sector after adding up all outputs and subtracting intermediate inputs. It is calculated without making deductions for depreciation of fabricated assets or depletion and degradation of natural resources. The industrial origin of value added is determined by the international Standard Industrial Calssification(ISIC), revision 3. Note: For for VAB countries gross value added at factor cost is ued as the denominator. FREE DATA FROM WORLD BANK VIA GAPMINDER.ORG, CC-BY LICENSE
  • Gini coeffcient: Gini shows income inequality in a society. A higher number means more inequality. FREE DATA FROM WORLD BANK VIA GAPMINDER.ORG, CC-BY LICENSE
  • Human Development Index (HDI): Human Development Index is an index used to rank countries by level of "human development". It contains three dimensions: health level, educational level and living standard. FREE DATA FROM WORLD BANK VIA GAPMINDER.ORG, CC-BY LICENSE

Questions planned to explore¶

The analysis is mostly directed to describe countries with high and low HDI level. It is assumed that a high HDI is desirable for any country. It will be tried to explore some highlevel metrics for each countries in order to try to discover any pattern or common characteristics for high and low HDI leve countries.

The gdp_cap is inclueded in the analysis as a metric of economic wellness for the country. We also want to understand whether this wellness is distributed or not, thus we include the gini coefficient. Also, we want to explore whether wellness and its distribution have any relation with the economic sectors percentage.

We will also try to observe whether there is any pattern or trend overtime.

It is an exploratory analysis, which intends to orient further investigation.

  1. Observe and understand each variable distribution (today, and "all-time")
  2. Observe and understand correlation between variables
  3. What is the trending over the years for each variable?
  4. What is the trending over the years for each variable, for high hdi level and low hdi level countries?
  5. What are the characteristics of countries, regarding gdp, economy composition, and gini value for each hdi level? How does it look comapre with some point in the past?
  6. What are the countries in the highest and lowet hdi levels? How does it look that list compare with some point in the past?

Creating Analytical Dataset¶

To get all the information in one dataframe, the following operations will be performed:

  • each of the datasets will be melted.(unpivoted).
  • Drop NA, since it is only needed the intersection between all individual datasets.
  • Each individual dataset will be joined, succesively with each other.
  • Thereafter, irrelevant columns will be dropped, and columns will be renamed.
  • Lastly the type for 'year' will be changed to integer.

  • economic sectors percentage Most of the countries develop very low amount of agriculture, and higher levels for services. The industry perc is below 0.32 for most of the countries.

2) Findings¶

  • gini has little correlation with hdi and gdp_cap, and no correlation with the other variables. This suggests that the chosen variables might not be quite relevant for understanding gini.
  • hdi has: strong correlation with gdp_cap, agriculture_perc. no correlation with industry_perc This suggests that the chosen variables might not be quite relevant for understanding hdi.
  • gdp_cap has low correlation with the economy sector percentage. This is relevant since it may imply that the productivity or efficiency of the resources does not strictly depends on the activity. Meaning that difference might be in the better use of them, and not in the activity perse. Since this is very high level analysis, further exploration may be needed regarding the details for each economic sector.

3) Findings¶

  • gdp_cap mean has been increased over the years. There is a clear jump up near 1995, and two step downs near 2000 and 2008. Further analysis is needed to review if there was any global crisis near those years. This also means that in the last years, the capacity to produce has inreased.
  • industry_perc mean has decreased over the years
  • agriculture_perc mean has decreased over the years
  • service_perc mean has increased over the years These last three points might imply that the most added value to the economy is in the service sector.
  • gini mean has decreased over the years (more equality)
  • hdi mean has increased over the years (more human development) These last two points mean that watching all the countries as a whole, humanity is getting better. However the timeframe is near 30 years, meaning (statiscally) that we might not be catching representative information.

5) Findings¶

Comparing 2000 and 2018 datasets:

  • gini mean: the mid-low group has seen the most significance change (increased). For the other groups it remains quite the same.
  • gdp_cap mean: for each group gdp_cap has decreased. the most for the mid_low
  • hdi mean: reamins very similar for all groups save but for low_low, for which it increased significantly compared to the other groups. This shows that despite being in the lowest ranked group, human development index is improving.
  • agr_perc mean: increases for all groups save but for the low_low.
  • ind_perc_mean: decreases for all goups. the most decrease is seen in the high_high group
  • srv_perc mean: remains the same for all groups save but for the high_high, for which it increases the most.

Insight:

To find patterns for HDI improvement it is suggested to further explore in the low_low group.

To find patterns for the gini improvement it is suggested to further explore in the mid_low group.

Conclusion¶

From individual variables datasets it was created one dataset to analyze and explore. The analysis has been oriented to discover relationships between hdi and other variables, such as gini, gdp_cap, and economy sectors percentage. It was explored each variable for each quartile of hdi level, en two differente time points. lastly, it is provided a detailed list of "stable" and "recent" countries for the highest and lowest hdi levels.

For each question the finding was provided.

To draw some general conclusions:

  • hdi is increasing
  • gini is increasing for mid hdi_level groups but decreasing for lowest and highest hdi_levels groups
  • industry_perc_mean is decreasing in all hdi groups
  • agriculture_perc mean increases for all groups save but the lowest hdi group.

Limitations¶

All analyzed variables are economic variables, save but the HDI. Therefore, a more deeper analysis including health, education, or maybe politics variables is needed to draw more conclusions. The analyzed period is the last 30 years. It might be not representative of "bigger" processes. Variables might not be significant or relevant to explore the HDI, since it showed strong correlation only with gdp_cap and agriculture_perc. Therefore, further investigation is needed, including other variables.
